# üêû bug report

### Affected Package
Angular 11.1  and 11.1.1 and likely previous releases

### Description

Each FormControl field of a FormGroup may be and should be initialized with undefined, like 
```js
	private createPhoneNumberForm(): FormGroup {
		return new FormGroup({
			fullNumber: new FormControl(undefined),
			id: new FormControl(undefined),
			entityId: new FormControl(undefined),
		}
		);
	}
```

if id or entityId is untouched, the value should remain undefined, rather than null. My backend respects and considers undefined, null and empty string of a JSON field. 

Currently after calling FormGroup.getRrawValue(), the raw data has the id field changed to null.
```
 raw: {"fullNumber":"0782828383","id":null,"entityId":null}
```

My workaround is to set the formControl value to undefined before calling getRawValue(), so the undefined field won't appear in the JSON payload. Rather clumsy. 


## üî¨ Minimal Reproduction

At https://stackblitz.com/angular/dqymemyngmr

Replace input-prefix-suffix-example.ts with this:
```js
import {Component, OnInit} from '@angular/core';
import { FormControl, FormBuilder, FormGroup, AbstractControl } from '@angular/forms';

/**
 * @title Inputs with prefixes and suffixes
 */
@Component({
  selector: 'input-prefix-suffix-example',
  templateUrl: 'input-prefix-suffix-example.html',
  styleUrls: ['input-prefix-suffix-example.css'],
})
export class InputPrefixSuffixExample  implements OnInit {
  model: PhoneNumber = {fullNumber: '0782828383'};

	phoneNumberForm: FormGroup;
  constructor(){
    this.phoneNumberForm=this.createPhoneNumberForm();
  }

	ngOnInit() {
		console.debug('phone model: ' + JSON.stringify(this.model));
		this.phoneNumberForm.patchValue(this.model);
		const raw = this.phoneNumberForm.getRawValue();
		console.debug('raw: '+ JSON.stringify(raw));
	}

	private createPhoneNumberForm(): FormGroup {
		return new FormGroup({
			fullNumber: new FormControl(undefined),
			id: new FormControl(undefined),
			entityId: new FormControl(undefined),
		}
		);
	}

  send(){
    const raw = this.phoneNumberForm.getRawValue();
    console.debug('raw: '+ JSON.stringify(raw));
    this.phoneNumberForm.controls['id'].setValue(undefined);
    const raw2 = this.phoneNumberForm.getRawValue();
    console.debug('raw2: '+ JSON.stringify(raw2));
  }
}

	export interface PhoneNumber {
		entityId?: string;
		fullNumber?: string;
		id?: number;
	}

```

And replace respective html with this:
```html
<form class="example-form" [formGroup]="phoneNumberForm">
  <mat-form-field class="example-full-width">
    <mat-label>Telephone</mat-label>
    <span matPrefix>+1 &nbsp;</span>
    <input type="tel" matInput formControlName="fullNumber">
    <mat-icon matSuffix (click)="send()">mode_edit</mat-icon>
  </mat-form-field>
</form>
```

You may check the browser console to see.


## üî• Exception or Error

This behavior causes the deserialization of my backend to fail, if I don't apply the workaround.


