Close #40387

Currently zone.js patch `setTimeout` and keep a `tasksByHandleId` map
to keep `timerId` <-> `ZoneTask` relationshio, so when `clearTimeout(timerId)`
is called, zone.js can find out the associated `ZoneTask`.
Now zone.js set the `tasksByHandleId` map in the `scheduleTask` function,
but if the `setTimeout` is running in the `FakeAsyncZoneSpec` or any other
`ZoneSpec` with `onScheduleTask` hooks. The `scheduleTask` in `timer` patch
may not be invoked.

For example:

```
fakeAsync(() => {
  setTimeout(() => {});
  tick();
});
```

In this case, the `timerId` kept in the `tasksByHandleId` map is not cleared,
since in the `FakeAsyncZoneSpec`, the `onScheduleTask` hook looks like this.

```
onScheduleTask(delegate, ..., task) {
  fakeAsyncScheduler.setTimeout(task);
  return task;
}
```

So `FakeAsyncZoneSpec` handle the task itself and doesn't call `parentDelegate.onScheduleTask`,
so the default `scheduleTask` in the `timer` patch is not invoked.

In this commit, the cleanup logic is moved from `scheduleTask` to `setTimeout` patch entry to
avoid memory leak.

